select "normal text" 5;
seln_delete;
textbox "normal text" xleft 1.73 ytop 2.11 text "At this temperature the ratio of nitrogen$n$molecules on the surface to underlying$n$nickel atoms is about 1.0; this is called$n$the coverage. There is no more room for$n$further adsorbed molecules, so this$n$surface is saturated." id 6;
run;
delay 19.300000;
stop;
seln_reset;
select "normal text" 6;
seln_delete;
textbox "normal text" xleft 1.72 ytop 2.3 text "The nitrogen molecules are tending$n$to sometimes pack in more closely than$n$a neat one-to-one arrangement, ignoring$n$the underlying pattern of nickel atoms.$n$This is called an incommensurate overlayer." id 7;
run;
delay 7.200000;
textbox "normal text" xleft 1.735 ytop 1.805 text "However, when the coverage happens$n$to drop lower, the nitrogens prefer to$n$sit between nickel atoms in an ordered,$n$commensurate overlayer. This is typical$n$for small molecules adsorbed on a surface." id 8;
delay 25.300000;
stop;
seln_reset;
seln_reset;
select "normal text" 7;
select "normal text" 8;
seln_delete;
textbox "normal text" xleft 1.73 ytop 2.205 text "A simple experiment that surface scientists$n$often perform to learn about adsorption is$n$to saturate a very cold surface with$n$molecules, and then watch the pressure$n$as the temperature is increased. This is$n$called thermal desorption spectroscopy.$n$We will do it now; try plotting pressure and$n$number of nitrogens adsorbed versus$n$temperature if you wish. (But don't start yet.)" id 9;
