textbox "normal text" xleft 0.165 ytop 2.06 text "Thermal desorption spectroscopy is easy to do in real experiments,$n$but difficult to describe thermodynamically. Three types of equilibrium$n$measurement directly give useful thermodynamic data:" id 18;
textbox "normal text" xleft 0.175 ytop 1.715 text "Isothermal measurements: the temperature is held constant while the pressure$n$    over the surface is varied and the equilibrium surface coverage measured.$n$$n$Isobaric measurements: the gas pressure is held constant while the temperature of$n$    the surface is varied and the equilibrium surface coverage measured.$n$$n$Isosteric measurements: the temperature and pressure are varied together so$n$    as to maintain a constant surface coverage. The heat of adsorption can then$n$    be obtained by an expression similar to the Clausius-Clapeyron equation.$n$$n$           (press a key when ready)" id 19;
